[{"id": "712a94de-cb9c-49b1-87cb-268915707769", "chunk_index": 0, "text": "USER: what's it called... like a facial reference right profile, straight on and left profile side by side. that type of thing have a name?\nASSISTANT: Yeah, that type of reference image has a few different names depending on the context:\n\n**Most common terms:**\n- **Turnaround** or **turnaround sheet** \u2014 especially in animation and character design, showing multiple views (front, side, back, sometimes 3/4) of a character\n- **Model sheet** \u2014 commonly used in animation studios to keep character consistency\n- **Reference sheet** or **ref sheet** \u2014 a broader term used by artists and the indie community^2^\n\n**More technical terms:**\n- **Orthographic reference** or **orthographic projection** \u2014 comes from engineering/drafting, referring to flat 2D views of a 3D object from different angles (front, side, top, etc.)^1,2^\n\nSo if you're looking for reference images to use for drawing or 3D modeling, searching for \"face turnaround\" or \"character model sheet\" should get you what you need. If it's specifically for 3D modeling purposes, \"orthographic reference\" is the precise technical term.", "embedding": [-0.10585659742355347, -0.04038675129413605, -0.05130121856927872, -0.014872380532324314, -0.03779109567403793, 0.0274957288056612, -0.01949489675462246, 0.05712178722023964, 0.030009916052222252, -0.01705552637577057, 0.03137010335922241, 0.004155329894274473, 0.03883115202188492, 0.04348388686776161, -0.012152529321610928, -0.03129104524850845, -0.0037332631181925535, 0.05647825077176094, 0.05437419191002846, 0.10588280856609344, 0.06510269641876221, -0.008812007494270802, -0.031554438173770905, -0.04900374636054039, -0.013544060289859772, -0.011314821429550648, -0.01055352482944727, -0.0095633240416646, 0.0045590768568217754, -0.0533103346824646, -0.0466369166970253, 0.034811340272426605, -0.053523194044828415, 0.010806452482938766, -0.04230101406574249, 0.046578139